  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting customer information\n- Verifying customer backgrounds\n- Screening against watchlists\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies\n- Training employees\n- Implementing monitoring systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n5. Legal Consequences\n- Potential fines\n- Criminal penalties\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n6. International Compliance Standards\n- Following guidelines from Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Adhering to global anti-money laundering standards\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
